nitrile to valine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals, montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH cycling and wet-dry fluctuations, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Partial hydrolysis/dephosphorylation of the N-phosphoroaminonitrile releases the corresponding free aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This transformation follows directly from the phosphoro-Strecker literature discussed in the research findings, which notes conversion of N-phosphoroaminonitriles to aminonitriles under changing pH or hydrolytic conditions (Gibard et al., 2018; Kim & Benner, 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-style alpha-ketoacid assembly to 2-ketoisovalerate from pyruvate and acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pool or mineral interface; non-enzymatic aldol-like carbon-carbon bond formation followed by oxidation-state adjustment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbon-carbon bond formation between pyruvate-derived enolate chemistry and a C2 carbonyl precursor yields the branched alpha-ketoacid 2-ketoisovalerate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature identifies 2-ketoisovalerate as the immediate biosynthetic precursor of valine and emphasizes alpha-ketoacids, pyruvate, and acetaldehyde as relevant prebiotic intermediates. Direct nonenzymatic prebiotic assembly of 2-ketoisovalerate is not well established in the supplied literature, so this step is explicitly a necessary speculative connector grounded in the reported alpha-ketoacid continuity problem between prebiotic and biotic chemistry (Muchowska et al., 2019; research synthesis citing alpha-ketoacids and the unresolved transition from Strecker to transamination pathways).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-style transamination/reductive amination of 2-ketoisovalerate to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pool, mineral interface, or compartment; NH3-rich, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amino-group transfer from a simple amino acid donor or direct reductive amination converts branched alpha-ketoacid to valine while regenerating an alpha-ketoacid partner.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research findings explicitly state that extant biochemistry makes valine from alpha-ketoacids via transamination and that analogous prebiotic conversion has been proposed as a bridge from cyanide chemistry to metabolism. Using glycine as amino donor creates a connected proto-metabolic network and recycles pyruvate (Parker et al., 2011; Muchowska et al., 2019; research synthesis on transamination-like continuity).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis during geothermal cycling or prolonged standing, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential nitrile hydration and amidic hydrolysis convert the aminonitrile to the amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the canonical completion step of Strecker synthesis. The literature summary explicitly states that aminonitriles hydrolyze to alpha-amino acids including valine under plausible prebiotic conditions (Miller, 1953; Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Parker et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Wet-dry condensation of valine to valylvaline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal wet-dry cycling or high-T/high-P episodes; peptide-forming concentration cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Dehydrative condensation forms a peptide bond between two valine molecules.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Including downstream peptide formation grounds valine in broader prebiotic assembly. The research findings cite wet-dry cycling as a plausible peptide route and specifically note abiotic valine peptide formation under high-temperature/high-pressure conditions (Furukawa et al., 2012; Rodriguez-Garcia et al., 2015).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal aldehyde to Strecker valine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 reduction in hydrothermal systems produces acetaldehyde, which enters a classic surface Strecker route to valine aminonitrile and then hydrolyzes to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde to cyanide-assisted Strecker valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde is transferred to the surface, converted photochemically with ammonia into cyanide feedstock, then combined with hydrothermal acetaldehyde in Strecker chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN to formamide-assisted valine route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN is first processed through formamide chemistry, then returned conceptually to the shared cyanide/carbonyl pool that feeds the Strecker branch to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker route to valine\",\n      \"description\": \"A diamidophosphate-mediated phosphoro-Strecker reaction forms N-phosphorovaline aminonitrile, which dephosphorylates to valine aminonitrile and hydrolyzes to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate to alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation forms pyruvate, which combines with acetaldehyde in a proto-metabolic alpha-ketoacid branch to 2-ketoisovalerate and then undergoes transamination-like conversion to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-supported hydrothermal pyruvate branch to valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Formate generated on Fe-S minerals participates in hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis, feeding the branched alpha-ketoacid route to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-first surface route with hydrothermal carbonyl input\",\n      \"description\": \"A surface cyanide pool and hydrothermal acetaldehyde converge directly in Strecker chemistry to valine aminonitrile and then valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde-assisted phosphoro-Strecker valine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde is converted to surface cyanide chemistry, which then enters the diamidophosphate-mediated phosphoro-Strecker branch toward valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker to valine followed by peptide capture\",\n      \"description\": \"Valine formed by Strecker hydrolysis is retained in the system by subsequent peptide-forming condensation, representing a selection/amplification route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Alpha-ketoacid continuity route from hydrothermal feedstocks\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal feedstocks generate both acetaldehyde and pyruvate; these converge on 2-ketoisovalerate, then amino-group transfer produces valine while regenerating pyruvate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Valine", "overall_strategy": "This network targets valine through convergent prebiotic routes centered on experimentally and theoretically supported intermediates from the literature: hydrogen cyanide, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, pyruvate, 2-ketoisovalerate, and valine aminonitrile. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced C1-C3 feedstocks such as formate, acetate, acetaldehyde, and pyruvate on iron-sulfur and oxide minerals under alkaline vent or subseafloor conditions. Surface environments convert HCN and carbonyl compounds into aminonitriles, sugars, and activated phosphorus-bearing intermediates under wet-dry and UV conditions, including Strecker and phosphoro-Strecker variants. Biochemical/prebiotic assembly then connects alpha-ketoacid chemistry to amino acid formation through transamination-like conversion of 2-ketoisovalerate to valine, aminonitrile hydrolysis to valine, and peptide formation. Ten distinct pathways are represented as alternative reaction sequences converging on the same target, while keeping all nodes in one connected bipartite network and highlighting unresolved steps as literature-grounded but partially speculative where valine-specific condition data are sparse.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "acetic acid", "common_name": "acetate/acetic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid/pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H8O3", "iupac_name": "3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "2-ketoisovalerate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H10N2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "valine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-4(2)5(6)3-7/h4-5H,6H2,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H11NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "valine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "CH6N3O3P", "iupac_name": "phosphoramidic diamide phosphate", "common_name": "diamidophosphate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H11N2O3P", "iupac_name": "N-phosphoro-2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "N-phosphoroaminonitrile of valine", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C10H20N2O3", "iupac_name": "2-[(2-amino-3-methylbutanoyl)amino]-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "valylvaline", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite, mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent-like, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface CO2 hydrogenation on Fe-S phases yields surface-bound formyl equivalents that desorb as formate.", "reasoning": "CO2 reduction to formate on Fe-S minerals is a core hydrothermal fixation step consistent with iron-sulfur world and vent chemistry; it provides a direct source of reduced one-carbon feedstock for downstream formaldehyde, formamide, and carbonyl chemistry relevant to valine precursors (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Russell & Martin, 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite, Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor/hydrothermal, strongly reducing, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Sequential reduction of CO2-derived C1 species and C-C coupling on Fe oxide/metal surfaces yields short-chain aldehydes.", "reasoning": "The literature report explicitly identifies formaldehyde and acetaldehyde as key small precursors and notes hydrothermal systems and reducing conditions as plausible sources of amino-acid precursors; magnetite-mediated Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry is used here as the hydrothermal mineral route required by the framework, while valine-specific product distributions remain sparse (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; research synthesis noting sparse direct valine data)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite, greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent/subseafloor interface, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "C1-C2 coupling and oxidation-state adjustment on mineral surfaces generates the alpha-keto acid pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is highlighted in the literature as a central prebiotic precursor and alpha-ketoacid hub. Direct pyruvate synthesis in hydrothermal settings is included in the framework and connects hydrothermal carbon fixation to later valine routes, though specific valine-focused hydrothermal pyruvate experiments remain limited (Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014; research synthesis on hydrothermal alpha-ketoacid relevance)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface photochemical conversion of HCN to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, evaporitic or geothermal surface setting, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "HCN hydration and photochemical rearrangement under UV-irradiated mineral surfaces produce formamide.", "reasoning": "The literature specifically notes UV photochemistry from HCN and water to formamide as a plausible surface route relevant to amino-acid and nucleobase chemistry, and hydrothermal formamide-based routes have been invoked for valine formation. This step supplies a cross-environment N-C feedstock (Saladino et al., 2012; Patel et al., 2015; research synthesis on surface/UV processes and formamide-based pathways)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface generation of HCN from formaldehyde-ammonia chemistry under UV", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2, sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV exposure, tidal flat or hot spring margin, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical dehydration/oxidation sequence from simple carbonyl-ammonia adduct chemistry generates cyanide-bearing products including HCN.", "reasoning": "The research synthesis identifies HCN and formaldehyde as robust prebiotic source molecules and surface/UV processes as relevant, though valine-specific mechanistic details remain incomplete. This connecting step is therefore literature-grounded but partially speculative, added to link hydrothermal formaldehyde supply to established cyanide-based valine chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2016; explicitly speculative connector due to sparse valine-specific data)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface Strecker synthesis of valine aminonitrile from acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral to mildly acidic aqueous conditions, evaporitic pool concentration, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Imine formation between carbonyl precursor and ammonia followed by cyanide addition yields alpha-aminonitrile corresponding to valine.", "reasoning": "The Strecker route is the strongest literature-supported prebiotic pathway for valine and proceeds through aminonitriles. Historical simulations of primitive-Earth chemistry detected valine among amino-acid products, and Strecker/Bucherer-Bergs frameworks are repeatedly cited as leading amino-acid routes (Miller, 1953; Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Parker et al., 2011). The exact carbonyl precursor to valine is often treated as branched aldehyde/ketone-like feedstock, and the present network uses acetaldehyde-centered branching as a connected approximation required to integrate the hydrothermal network."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface phosphoro-Strecker synthesis to N-phosphorovaline aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals, montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "near-neutral pH, wet-dry concentration, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Diamidophosphate activates carbonyl-cyanide-amino chemistry to give N-phosphoroaminonitrile selectively from aldehydic substrate.", "reasoning": "The literature specifically identifies phosphoro-Strecker chemistry with diamidophosphate at near-neutral pH as a plausible prebiotic route to N-phosphoroaminonitriles, which can then hydrolyze or convert to aminonitriles. This route is incorporated as an alternative valine-precursor channel (Kim & Benner, 2021; Gibard et al., 2018; research synthesis citing phosphoro-Strecker variants)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface hydrolysis/dephosphorylation of N-phosphorovaline aminonitrile to valine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals, montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH cycling and wet-dry fluctuations, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Partial hydrolysis/dephosphorylation of the N-phosphoroaminonitrile releases the corresponding free aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "This transformation follows directly from the phosphoro-Strecker literature discussed in the research findings, which notes conversion of N-phosphoroaminonitriles to aminonitri