ay because it reflects literature continuity from hydrothermal reduced-carbon chemistry to alpha-ketoacid chemistry and then to amino acid formation. CO2 reduction to formate is plausible, and pyruvate as a protometabolic hub is reasonable. The major flaw is rxn_009: direct assembly of 2-ketoisovalerate from pyruvate + acetaldehyde is not a standard or well-supported prebiotic step. In biology, branched-chain amino acid synthesis proceeds via acetolactate-type chemistry from two pyruvate equivalents, not pyruvate + acetaldehyde. The final transamination-like conversion is plausible as a prebiotic analogy but somewhat speculative.', 'The formate-supported hydrothermal branch is topologically coherent, but the chemistry is still limited by speculative carbon-carbon bond construction to 2-ketoisovalerate. The route is appealing from a network perspective yet under-supported experimentally for valine specifically.', 'This route depends on two weak steps in sequence: nonstandard HCN generation from formaldehyde/ammonia and incorrect Strecker carbon accounting for valine aminonitrile. As written, it is not a credible valine pathway.', 'This pathway benefits from general literature support for phosphoro-Strecker chemistry, but it inherits the incorrect choice of acetaldehyde for valine-carbon-skeleton generation. It is therefore only moderately aligned with the literature at the conceptual level, not at the reaction-specific level.', 'Peptide capture by wet-dry condensation is plausible and supported in a broad prebiotic sense, but the route remains compromised by the incorrect valine aminonitrile precursor step. If the amino acid node were produced correctly, the peptide extension would be one of the stronger parts of the network.', 'This pathway captures the desirable literature theme of continuity from hydrothermal feedstocks to alpha-ketoacid chemistry and finally amino acid synthesis. However, the pivotal conversion to 2-ketoisovalerate is poorly justified and currently the main barrier to approval.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Valine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network follows literature-supported prebiotic themes for valine synthesis by converging on two major immediate precursor classes: (i) the branched \u03b1-ketoacid 3-methyl-2-oxobanoate (2-ketoisovalerate), which is then aminated/transaminated to valine in a biochemistry-like prebiotic step, and (ii) the corresponding \u03b1-aminonitrile/hydantoin class produced by Strecker or phosphoro-Strecker chemistry and hydrolyzed to valine. Hydrothermal reactions generate reduced C1-C3 feedstocks such as formate, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, pyruvate, and ammonia-bearing reduced carbon; surface settings use cyanide chemistry, photochemistry, borate-stabilized carbonyl chemistry, and wet-dry concentration to produce aminonitriles and branched ketoacid precursors; biochemical/prebiotic settings complete hydrolysis, transamination, and peptide capture. Because the literature summary contains limited valine-specific reaction-level detail for some branch-forming steps, several connecting reactions are explicitly marked as speculative but are constrained to known prebiotic frameworks emphasized in the cited literature.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"dihydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\