hi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H10N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-isopropylimidazolidine-2,4-dione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valine hydantoin\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 with H2 to surface-bound formyl/formate species that desorb into solution.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Directly follows the hydrothermal CO2 reduction framework emphasized for alkaline vents and Fe-S minerals, with greigite and mackinawite as required mineral catalysts; this supplies reduced C1 carbon feeding later carbonyl and formamide chemistry. Supported broadly by iron-sulfur world and vent CO2 reduction literature (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Cody et al., 2000).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Magnetite/Fe0 Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde from reduced C1 carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor hydrothermal, anoxic, reducing\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential hydrogenation and C-C coupling of reduced carbon on metal oxide/metal surfaces produces small aldehydes including formaldehyde and acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction implements the literature-supported hydrothermal production of simple aldehydes from reduced carbon under Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions and connects hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface Strecker and cyanide chemistry. Product classes are supported broadly though selectivity is uncertain; included as a necessary connector constrained by hydrothermal FTT literature and the report's emphasis on formaldehyde-based prebiotic chemistry (Cody et al., 2000; McCollom & Seewald, 2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2/H2 on Fe-S and magnetite surfaces\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent to subseafloor interface, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-mediated reduction and carbon-carbon assembly generate \u03b1-ketoacid products, with pyruvate as a protometabolic hub.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report specifically identifies pyruvate as a prebiotically relevant \u03b1-ketoacid hub in hydrothermal and protometabolic settings. Exact valine-specific yield data are absent, so this step is a literature-guided protometabolic connector rather than a valine-specific demonstrated synthesis. Supported by protometabolism literature around pyruvate/glyoxylate networks and hydrothermal carbon fixation (Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photochemical generation of HCN/formamide pool from formaldehyde- and nitrogen-bearing feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated tidal flat or geothermal pool, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-assisted surface redox chemistry generates cyanide-bearing and formamide-bearing nitrogen-carbon species from simple carbonyl and nitrogen feedstocks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report highlights cyanide/formaldehyde chemistry, UV-driven processes, and formamide-based pathways as central to prebiotic amino-acid precursor generation, though valine-specific mechanistic details are sparse. This connector is therefore partially speculative but aligned with the literature's cyanide-formamide framework and required surface photochemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Saladino et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Borate-stabilized carbonyl concentration and pyruvate-forming surface chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool with wet-dry concentration cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Concentration and stabilization of reactive carbonyl species enables aldol-like and redox transformations feeding \u03b1-ketoacid formation, reinforcing pyruvate as a network hub.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly identifies formaldehyde-based carbonyl chemistry and pyruvate as relevant prebiotic intermediates. Exact pyruvate-forming sequences under these conditions are incompletely defined for valine, so this is a constrained bridging reaction representing carbonyl concentration chemistry in surface settings. Broadly supported by formose/carbonyl network literature and protometabolic pyruvate relevance (Benner et al., 2012; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate self-condensation to acetolactate-like branched \u03b1-keto precursor\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling in concentrated evaporitic or geothermal pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Base- and mineral-assisted coupling of two pyruvate equivalents produces a branched \u03b1-hydroxy-\u03b1-keto acid analogous to acetolactate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step corrects the previous failed attempt by using two pyruvate equivalents rather than pyruvate plus acetaldehyde, matching known branched-chain ketoacid logic from extant valine biosynthesis. The report emphasizes \u03b1-ketoacid continuity with biochemistry, but direct prebiotic experimental validation for this exact condensation is limited; therefore this step is explicitly speculative yet chemically constrained and necessary to connect pyruvate to 2-ketoisovalerate (Berg et al., 2002 for biochemical precedent; Muchowska et al., 2019 for prebiotic \u03b1-ketoacid relevance; the valine-specific gap is acknowledged in the literature summary).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal dehydration/rearrangement of acetolactate to 2-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals/borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"dry-heating phase of wet-dry cycle, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Concentrative dehydration and keto-enol rearrangement convert the branched precursor into the more stable branched \u03b1-ketoacid 2-ketoisovalerate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This provides the immediate biochemical-style precursor to valine identified in the research report. Direct prebiotic demonstration remains incomplete, so the reaction is a literature-constrained connecting step justified by the report's explicit designation of 2-ketoisovalerate as valine's immediate precursor and by the broader need for continuity between prebiotic and biotic routes (White, 1976; Muchowska et al., 2019; literature gap acknowledged in the report's unresolved-challenges section).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical Strecker synthesis of valine aminonitrile from 2-ketoisovalerate, ammonia, and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral to mildly acidic aqueous pool, concentrated by evaporation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia adds to the ketoacid carbonyl to form an imine/iminium equivalent, followed by cyanide addition to give the corresponding \u03b1-aminonitrile precursor of valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step follows the literature's central Strecker logic while correcting the earlier carbon-skeleton error: valine-class aminonitrile must derive from a C5 branched carbonyl precursor, not acetaldehyde. The report strongly supports Strecker aminonitrile chemistry as a major prebiotic route to amino acids and emphasizes \u03b1-ketoacids as key intermediates connecting to biochemistry (Miller, 1953; Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Weber & Miller, 1981; Commeyras et al., 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker formation of N-phosphoro-valine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"near-neutral pH, evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Diamidophosphate activates aminonitrile formation through N-phosphorylation, biasing capture of the carbonyl substrate into an N-phosphoroaminonitrile intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly identifies phosphoro-Strecker chemistry with diamidophosphate as a plausible prebiotic route to N-phosphoroaminonitriles under near-neutral conditions. This branch provides a second literature-grounded route to the same valine aminonitrile manifold and improves network convergence (Krishnamurthy et al., 2018; Chandru et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Conversion of N-phosphoro-valine aminonitrile to valine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH drift during pond cycling enables dephosphorylation/hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolytic dephosphorylation releases the free aminonitrile from its phosphoro-protected precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This directly implements the literature summary that N-phosphoroaminonitriles can be converted to aminonitriles or hydrolysis products under changing pH conditions. It is therefore closely aligned with the cited phosphoro-Strecker framework (Krishnamurthy et al., 2018; Chandru et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs-type capture of valine precursor as hydantoin\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals/TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed shallow pool with carbonate/cyanide chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The branched carbonyl precursor enters cyanide/ammonia-derived ring-forming chemistry to give a hydantoin-class intermediate corresponding to valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature report explicitly notes B\u00fccherer-Bergs/hydantoin chemistry as a recognized prebiotic amino-acid route relevant to valine precursors. Exact prebiotic environmental execution remains less defined than classical Strecker, so this is included as a literature-supported alternative precursor branch (Or\u00f3 & Kimball, 1961; reported in the summary via B\u00fccherer-Bergs route discussion).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile and valine hydantoin to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal pool or hydrothermal overprint with prolonged aqueous exposure\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aqueous nitrile and/or hydantoin hydrolysis yields the free \u03b1-amino acid valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the canonical completion step of Strecker chemistry, and hydantoin hydrolysis is likewise a recognized route to amino acids. This step is central to the literature-supported prebiotic conversion of valine precursors to valine (Miller, 1953; Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Or\u00f3 & Kimball, 1961).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Prebiotic transamination/reductive amination of 2-ketoisovalerate to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mineral interface or concentrated pool; amino-group transfer/reductive amination analogue\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The branched \u03b1-ketoacid accepts nitrogen through transamination-like or reductive amination chemistry to furnish valine directly.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report specifically highlights transamination of \u03b1-ketoacids as the extant biochemical route to valine and suggests prebiotic analogues could bridge cyanide chemistry and metabolism. Included as a direct biochemistry-like route from the immediate precursor 2-ketoisovalerate to valine (Miller, 1957 conceptually for amino acid chemistry; Commeyras et al., 2004; Muchowska et al., 2019; continuity challenge acknowledged in the report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Wet-dry peptide condensation of valine to valylvaline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm to elevated\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry or high-T/high-P cycling; peptide-forming concentration regime\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Repeated dehydration-condensation links two valine molecules via a peptide bond.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly notes abiotic formation of valine peptides under high-temperature/high-pressure conditions and more generally peptide formation under dry-wet cycling. This provides downstream capture of valine into prebiotic oligomers (Furukawa et al., 2012; Rodriguez-Garcia et al., 2015).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal ketoacid-to-valine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct vent-generated pyruvate feeds branched ketoacid formation and then prebiotic transamination to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate to Strecker valine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent pyruvate is converted to 2-ketoisovalerate, then enters classical Strecker chemistry and aminonitrile hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate to phosphoro-Strecker valine route\",\n      \"description\": \"The branched \u03b1-ketoacid formed from pyruvate is trapped as an N-phosphoroaminonitrile before release and hydrolysis to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate to hydantoin valine route\",\n      \"description\": \"A branched \u03b1-ketoacid precursor formed from pyruvate is diverted into hydantoin chemistry and hydrolyzed to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduced C1 hydrothermal route to Strecker valine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 reduction to formate and aldehydes feeds surface cyanide generation, reinforcing a Strecker route to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduced C1 hydrothermal route to phosphoro-Strecker valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced carbon feeds surface cyanide and branched ketoacid chemistry, then DAP-mediated phosphoro-Strecker chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduced C1 hydrothermal route to hydantoin valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Aldehyde and cyanide generation from hydrothermal feedstocks ultimately support a hydantoin-based valine precursor route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface carbonyl concentration to direct transamination valine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface borate/clay chemistry generates pyruvate, which becomes 2-ketoisovalerate and then valine without cyanide hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker branch to peptide-captured valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Classical Strecker chemistry yields valine, which is then sequestered in peptide form during later prebiotic condensation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-biochemical continuity route\",\n      \"description\": \"This pathway emphasizes continuity from vent pyruvate and reduced C1 chemistry through a branched \u03b1-ketoacid hub to valine and valine peptide products.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Valine", "overall_strategy": "This network follows literature-supported prebiotic themes for valine synthesis by converging on two major immediate precursor classes: (i) the branched \u03b1-ketoacid 3-methyl-2-oxobanoate (2-ketoisovalerate), which is then aminated/transaminated to valine in a biochemistry-like prebiotic step, and (ii) the corresponding \u03b1-aminonitrile/hydantoin class produced by Strecker or phosphoro-Strecker chemistry and hydrolyzed to valine. Hydrothermal reactions generate reduced C1-C3 feedstocks such as formate, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, pyruvate, and ammonia-bearing reduced carbon; surface settings use cyanide chemistry, photochemistry, borate-stabilized carbonyl chemistry, and wet-dry concentration to produce aminonitriles and branched ketoacid precursors; biochemical/prebiotic settings complete hydrolysis, transamination, and peptide capture. Because the literature summary contains limited valine-specific reaction-level detail for some branch-forming steps, several connecting reactions are explicitly marked as speculative but are constrained to known prebiotic frameworks emphasized in the cited literature.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "dihydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C4H6O2", "iupac_name": "3-hydroxy-3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "acetolactate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H8O3", "iupac_name": "3-methyl-2-oxobanoic acid", "common_name": "2-ketoisovaleric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H10N2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "valine aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "valine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C10H18N2O3", "iupac_name": "2-[(2-amino-3-methylbutanoyl)amino]-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "valylvaline", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "CH4N2O2P", "iupac_name": "phosphorylamidic diamide", "common_name": "diamidophosphate", "inchi": null, "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H11N2O3P", "iupac_name": "N-phosphoro-2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "N-phosphoro-valine aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C6H10N2O2", "iupac_name": "5-isopropylimidazolidine-2,4-dione", "common_name": "valine hydantoin", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 with H2 to surface-bound formyl/formate species that desorb into solution.", "reasoning": "Directly follows the hydrothermal CO2 reduction framework emphasized for alkaline vents and Fe-S minerals, with greigite and mackinawite as required mineral catalysts; this supplies reduced C1 carbon feeding later carbonyl and formamide chemistry. Supported broadly by iron-sulfur world and vent CO2 reduction literature (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Cody et al., 2000)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Magnetite/Fe0 Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde from reduced C1 carbon", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal, anoxic, reducing"}, "mechanism": "Sequential hydrogenation and C-C coupling of reduced carbon on metal oxide/metal surfaces produces small aldehydes including formaldehyde and acetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This reaction implements the literature-supported hydrothermal production of simple aldehydes from reduced carbon under Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions and connects hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface Strecker and cyanide chemistry. Product classes are supported broadly though selectivity is uncertain; included as a necessary connector constrained by hydrothermal FTT literature and the report's emphasis on formaldehyde-based prebiotic chemistry (Cody et al., 2000; McCollom & Seewald, 2007)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2/H2 on Fe-S and magnetite surfaces", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent to subseafloor interface, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Surface-mediated reduction and carbon-carbon assembly generate \u03b1-ketoacid products, with pyruvate as a protometabolic hub.", "reasoning": "The research report specifically identifies pyruvate as a prebiotically relevant \u03b1-ketoacid hub in hydrothermal and protometabolic settings. Exact valine-specific yield data are absent, so this step is a literature-guided protometabolic connector rather than a valine-specific demonstrated synthesis. Supported by protometabolism literature around pyruvate/glyoxylate networks and hydrothermal carbon fixation (Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface photochemical generation of HCN/formamide pool from formaldehyde- and nitrogen-bearing feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004", "mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated tidal flat or geothermal pool, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "UV-assisted surface redox chemistry generates cyanide-bearing and formamide-bearing nitrogen-carbon species from simple carbonyl and nitrogen feedstocks.", "reasoning": "The report highlights cyanide/formaldehyde chemistry, UV-driven processes, and formamide-based pathways as central to prebiotic amino-acid precursor generation, though valine-specific mechanistic details are sparse. This connector is therefore partially speculative but aligned with the literature's cyanide-formamide framework and required surface photochemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Saladino et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Borate-stabilized carbonyl concentration and pyruvate-forming surface chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool with wet-dry concentration cycles"}, "mechanism": "Concentration and stabilization of reactive carbonyl species enables aldol-like and redox transformations feeding \u03b1-ketoacid formation, reinforcing pyruvate as a network hub.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly identifies formaldehyde-based carbonyl chemistry and pyruvate as relevant prebiotic intermediates. Exact pyruvate-forming sequences under these conditions are incompletely defined for valine, so this is a constrained bridging reaction representing carbonyl concentration chemistry in surface settings. Broadly supported by formose/carbonyl network literature and protometabolic pyruvate relevance (Benner et al., 2012; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Pyruvate self-condensation to acetolactate-like branched \u03b1-keto precursor", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite/phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycling in concentrated evaporitic or geothermal pool"}, "mechanism": "Base- and mineral-assisted coupling of two pyruvate equivalents produces a branched \u03b1-hydroxy-\u03b1-keto acid analogous to acetolactate.", "reasoning": "This step corrects the previous failed attempt by using two pyruvate equivalents rather than pyruvate plus acetaldehyde, matching known branched-chain ketoacid logic from extant valine biosynthesis. The report emphasizes \u03b1-ketoacid continuity with biochemistry, but direct prebiotic experimental validation for this exact condensation is limited; therefore this step is explicitly speculative yet chemically constrained and necessary to connect pyruvate to 2-ketoisovalerate (Berg et al., 2002 for biochemical precedent; Muchowska et al., 2019 for prebiotic \u03b1-ketoacid relevance; the valine-specific gap is acknowledged in the literature summary)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Thermal dehydration/rearrangement of acetolactate to 2-ketoisovalerate", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals/borate minerals", "aqueous": "false", "other": "dry-heating phase of wet-dry cycle, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Concentrative dehydration and keto-enol rearrangement convert the branched precursor into the more stable branched \u03b1-ketoacid 2-ketoisovalerate.", "reasoning": "This provides the immediate biochemical-style precursor to valine identified in the research report. Direct prebiotic demonstration remains incomplete, so the reaction is a literature-constrained connecting step justified by the report's explicit designation of 2-ketoisovalerate as valine's immediate precursor and by the broader need for continuity between prebiotic and biotic routes (White, 1976; Muchowska et al., 2019; literature gap acknowledged in the report's unresolved-challenges section)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Classical Strecker synthesis of valine aminonitrile from 2-ketoisovalerate, ammonia, and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral to mildly acidic aqueous pool, concentrated by evaporation"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia adds to the ketoacid carbonyl to form an imine/iminium equivalent, followed by cyanide addition to give the corresponding \u03b1-aminonitrile precursor of valine.", "reasoning": "This step follows the literature's central Strecker logic while correcting the earlier carbon-skeleton error: valine-class aminonitrile must derive from a C5 branched carbonyl precursor, not acetaldehyde. The report strongly supports Strecker aminonitrile chemistry as a major prebiotic route to amino acids and emphasizes \u03b1-ketoacids as key intermediates connecting to biochemistry (Miller, 1953; Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Weber & Miller, 1981; Commeyras et al., 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Phosphoro-Strecker formation of N-phosphoro-valine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "near-neutral pH, evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Diamidophosphate activates aminonitrile formation through N-phosphorylation, biasing capture of the carbonyl substrate into an N-phosphoroaminonitrile intermediate.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly identifies phosphoro-Strecker chemistry with diamidophosphate as a plausible prebiotic route to N-phosphoroaminonitriles under near-neutral conditions. This branch provides a second literature-grounded route to the same valine aminonitrile manifold and improves network convergence (Krishnamurthy et al., 2018; Chandru et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Conversion of N-phosphoro-valine aminonitrile to valine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH drift during pond cycling enables dephosphorylation/hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolytic dephosphorylation releases the free aminonitrile from its phosphoro-protected precursor.", "reasoning": "This directly implements the literature summary that N-phosphoroaminonitriles can be converted to aminonitriles or hydrolysis products under changing pH conditions. It is therefore closely aligned with the cited phosphoro-Strecker framework (Krishnamurthy et al., 2018; Chandru et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs-type capture of valine precursor as hydantoin", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals/TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed shallow pool with carbonate/cyanide chemistry"}, "mechanism": "The branched carbonyl precursor enters cyanide/ammonia-derived ring-forming chemistry to give a hydantoin-class intermediate corresponding to valine.", "reasoning": "The literature report explicitly notes B\u00fccherer-Bergs/hydantoin chemistry as a recognized prebiotic amino-acid route relevant to valine precursors. Exact prebiotic environmental execution remains less defined than classical Strecker, so this is included as a literature-supported alternative precursor branch (Or\u00f3 & Kimball, 1961; reported in the summary via B\u00fccherer-Bergs route discussion)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile and valine hydantoin to valine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "geothermal pool or hydrothermal overprint with prolonged aqueous exposure"}, "mechanism": "Aqueous nitrile and/or hydantoin hydrolysis yields the free \u03b1-amino acid valine.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the canonical completion step of Strecker chemistry, and hydantoin hydrolysis is likewise a recognized route to amino acids. This step is central to the literature-supported prebiotic conversion of valine precursors to valine (Miller, 1953; Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Or\u00f3 & Kimball, 1961)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Prebiotic transamination/reductive amination of 2-ketoisovalerate to valine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "mineral interface or concentrated pool; amino-group transfer/reductive amination analogue"}, "mechanism": "The branched \u03b1-ketoacid accepts nitrogen through transamination-like or reductive amination chemistry to furnish valine directly.", "reasoning": "The research report specifically highlights transamination of \u03b1-ketoacids as the extant biochemical route to valine and suggests prebiotic analogues could bridge cyanide chemistry and metabolism. Included as a direct biochemistry-like route from the immediate precursor 2-ketoisovalerate to valine (Miller, 1957 conceptually for amino acid chemistry; Commeyras et al., 2004; Muchowska et al., 2019; continuity challenge acknowledged in the report)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Wet-dry peptide condensation of valine to valylvaline", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-400K", "pressure": "1 atm to elevated", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry or high-T/high-P cycling; peptide-forming concentration regime"}, "mechanism": "Repeated dehydration-condensat