way_coherence\": 0.63,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.74,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.66,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.56,\n      \"feedback\": \"This route suffers from the most severe chemical gap: condensation of pyruvate and acetaldehyde to 2-ketoisovalerate is plausible only through a more detailed aldol/rearrangement sequence, not as a single concentrated surface step. The final transamination/reductive amination remains uncertain. While surface concentration chemistry is a valid concept, the specific carbon-skeleton construction is too compressed and speculative.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_007\",\n        \"rxn_015\",\n        \"rxn_002\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Expand pyruvate + acetaldehyde chemistry into explicit intermediates such as hydroxy-ketoacids or branched aldehydes.\",\n        \"Provide borate/clay/mineral context and pH control for any aldol-based branching chemistry.\",\n        \"Use a better-supported valine-forming terminal step, such as aminonitrile hydrolysis, if keeping the branched ketoacid.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.56,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.28,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.71,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.82\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.58,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.69,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.64,\n      \"feedback\": \"The back end of the route is relatively strong because aminonitrile formation and hydrolysis are literature-supported themes. The weakness remains the unsupported direct generation of 2-ketoisovalerate from pyruvate and acetaldehyde on the surface. This makes the route only moderately plausible despite a reasonable target-forming finish.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_007\"\n      ],\n     